2026-04-16 12:16:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal wiring between relay output and output terminals', 'ambient sensor module switched‑cables indicator/series path'] hypothesis_explanation='The control (ambient sensor) module reports ~12 V at the relay output positive node and ~0.36 V at the relay output negative node relative to ground, indicating the relay itself is correctly switching full battery across its contacts. However, at the plug going to the load module only ~0.36 V appears (and that same ~0.36 V is seen across the load‑module diode and input terminals), meaning almost the entire 12 V is being dropped somewhere between the relay output node and the module’s external output terminals.\n\nBecause polarity and inter‑module cabling have been visually confirmed correct, and the load module input sees only the small residual voltage, the fault must lie inside the ambient sensor (control) module, downstream of the relay contacts: most likely a mis‑wired or high‑resistance path (e.g., wrong internal connection, damaged trace, or incorrectly placed indicator LED/resistor network) between the relay’s switched node and the external output pins. This would leave the relay energized with 12 V present internally but prevent full supply from reaching the load module, explaining why the lamp never lights now despite the relay output measurement. Repair involves correcting/replacing the internal wiring or PCB connection from the relay switched contact to the module’s output terminals (and any series indicator circuit in that path).'
