DESCRIPTION: With the system powered and PSU negative as reference, probe the voltage on the control module’s OUTPUT (+) terminal directly on the PCB just inside the box, then on the mating fast‑connector pin on the control module cable, and finally on the corresponding mating pin on the load‑module cable. Compare these readings to the 11.99 V present at the relay contact to determine whether the ~0.36 V seen at the load module is caused by a high‑resistance joint, damaged fast connector, or broken conductor between the relay output and the load input.,
RESULT: At the control relay, the output terminal shows 11.99 V on (+) and 0.36 V on (−), matching the expected relay contact voltage. At both the control output cable (+) and the load input cable (+), the measured voltage is only ~0.36 V on both (+) and (−), indicating that the 11.99 V from the relay is not present past the relay-to-cable interface. The ~0.36 V seen at the load module is therefore consistent with a high‑resistance joint, damaged fast connector, or open conductor between the relay output and the control output cable.
