description: With modules connected as currently wired and the control‑module relay confirmed to have about 12 V between its two output terminals, measure the voltage directly across the two load‑module input terminals, then measure across the diode in the load module (anode to cathode) while the lamp is expected to be on. This will reveal whether the load module is actually receiving full supply and whether the diode is shorted, open, or reverse‑biased., outcome='The load module input is seeing about 0.36 V on the (+) terminal and near 0 V on the (−) terminal. The protection diode has about 0.36 V from anode to cathode, consistent with the measured load input terminals.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor module common (negative) rail and its connection to power supply and load modules,
description: Measure the voltage of the ambient sensor module’s negative/output‑return terminal relative to the battery negative at the power‑supply module, and also relative to the load‑module negative input terminal, while the system is powered. Verify whether the control module’s “0 V” rail is actually bonded to the supply negative or is floating several hundred millivolts above it, and whether there is any unexpected series resistance or diode drop in this return path., outcome='The control module “0 V” rail (Control Output Cable −) is effectively at the same potential as the PSU Output Cable (−), differing by only about 0.3 mV. The Load Input Cable (−) is also at the same potential, within about 0.3 mV of the PSU negative. No significant additional series resistance or diode drop is indicated in the return path based on these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module positive rail between input terminal and relay output,
description: With the modules interconnected as now and the PSU LED on, measure the DC voltage at three points relative to PSU negative: (1) the control‑module positive INPUT terminal, (2) the node feeding the relay coil / light‑sensor circuitry, and (3) the relay POSITIVE OUTPUT contact feeding the external output cables. Confirm whether 12 V is present at the control input but drops to about 0.3–0.4 V by the time it reaches the relay output, which would indicate an unintended series element or partial open in the control module’s positive path., outcome='Voltage at the Control Input Cable (+) is approximately 11.99 V relative to PSU negative.  \nAt the Control Relay, the positive side is at approximately 11.99 V and the negative side is at approximately 0.36 V relative to PSU negative.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=65.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output positive terminal and associated fast-connector pair,
description: With the system powered and PSU negative as reference, probe the voltage on the control module’s OUTPUT (+) terminal directly on the PCB just inside the box, then on the mating fast‑connector pin on the control module cable, and finally on the corresponding mating pin on the load‑module cable. Compare these readings to the 11.99 V present at the relay contact to determine whether the ~0.36 V seen at the load module is caused by a high‑resistance joint, damaged fast connector, or broken conductor between the relay output and the load input., outcome='At the control relay, the output terminal shows 11.99 V on (+) and 0.36 V on (−), matching the expected relay contact voltage. At both the control output cable (+) and the load input cable (+), the measured voltage is only ~0.36 V on both (+) and (−), indicating that the 11.99 V from the relay is not present past the relay-to-cable interface. The ~0.36 V seen at the load module is therefore consistent with a high‑resistance joint, damaged fast connector, or open conductor between the relay output and the control output cable.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output (+) routing / PCB around relay contact,
description: With the control module still open, use a continuity tester or ohmmeter (power removed) to trace the copper path from the relay output (+) contact pad to the output (+) terminal pad where the cable/fast‑connector attaches, including any intermediate test pads, vias, or series components. Identify whether there is an unintended series component (e.g., resistor, indicator LED, or protective device) or an alternate branch that ties this node to the ~0.36 V level instead of directly to the 12 V relay contact., outcome='Continuity from the Control Relay output to the Control Output Cable (+) is a direct short, with measured resistance of 0.01 Ω. No unintended series components or alternate branches were detected along this path in this test.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=40.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
